{{Refimprove|date=September 2018}} [[File:LondonSmog.jpg|thumb|{{largethumb}}|2004 filming of a 19th-century film scene set in [[London]]]] The term '''historical period drama''' (also '''historical drama''', '''period drama''', '''costume drama''', and '''period piece''') refers to a work set in a past time period, usually used in the context of [[film]] and [[television]]. It is an informal crossover term that can apply to several [[genre]]s and is often heard in the context of [[historical fiction]] and [[romance film|romance]]s, [[adventure film]]s, and [[swashbuckler]]s. A period piece may be set in a vague or general era such as the [[Middle Ages]] or a specific period such as the [[Roaring Twenties]]. A religious work can qualify as period drama but not as historical drama.
==Historical accuracy== Some works attempt to accurately portray historical events or persons, to the degree that the available historical research and the length of the work will allow. These types of works are also known as [[docudrama]], examples being ''[[Cinderella Man]]'', ''[[Schindler's List]]'', and ''[[Lincoln (film)|Lincoln]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZcGNAQAAQBAJ|title=Inspired by True Events: An Illustrated Guide to More Than 500 History-Based Films, 2nd Edition: An Illustrated Guide to More Than 500 History-Based Films|last=Niemi|first=Robert|date=2013-10-17|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781610691987|language=en}}</ref> Other works are fictionalized stories based on actual people or events, such as ''[[Braveheart]]'' and ''[[Les Misérables (2012 film)|Les Misérables]]''.
==Examples== {{main|List of historical period drama films}} Film and television examples of period pieces include ''[[Marie Antoinette (1938 film)|Marie Antoinette]]'' (1938), ''[[Barry Lyndon]]'' (1975), ''[[Amadeus (film)|Amadeus]]'' (1984), [[The Age of Innocence (1993 film)|''The Age of Innocence'']] (1993), ''[[Last Man Standing (1996 film)|Last Man Standing]]'' (1996), ''[[Shakespeare in Love]]'' (1998), ''[[The Young Victoria]]'' (2009) and ''[[Darkest Hour (film)|Darkest Hour]]'' (2017).
Examples of television series include ''[[Robin Hood (1953 TV series)|Robin Hood]]'' (1953), ''[[Middlemarch (TV serial)|Middlemarch]]'' (1994), ''[[Pride and Prejudice (1995 TV series)|Pride and Prejudice]]'' (1995), ''[[The Tudors]]'', ''[[Mad Men]]'', ''[[Boardwalk Empire]]'', ''[[Call the Midwife]]'', ''[[Downton Abbey]]'', ''[[Deadwood (TV series)|Deadwood]]'', ''[[Halt and Catch Fire (TV series)|Halt and Catch Fire]]'', ''[[Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman]]'', ''[[Father Brown (1974 TV series)|Father Brown]]'', ''[[Stranger Things]]'', ''[[The Americans (2013 TV series)|The Americans]]'', ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]'', ''[[That '70s Show]]'', ''[[The Get Down]]'', ''[[Another Period]]'', ''[[Better Call Saul]]'' and ''[[The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel]]''.
==See also== * [[List of films about the American Revolution]] * [[List of films and television shows about the American Civil War]] *[[Historical fiction]] *[[Sword-and-sandal]] * [[List of films set in ancient Rome]] * [[Western films]] *[[Asian historical period drama films]] **''[[Jidaigeki]]'' **''[[Wuxia]]'' **''[[Sageuk]]'' **''[[List of Vietnamese historical period drama films|Phim lịch sử]]'' * [[Middle Ages in film]] *[[War film]]
