{{notability|date=March 2018}}
{{Infobox building |name = Tea House in Aghdam |native_name = Ağdamda Çay Evi |image = |caption = |former_names = |building_type = |architectural_style = |structural_system = |location = [[Agdam]], [[Azerbaijan]] {{flagicon|Azerbaijan}} |owner = |current_tenants = |landlord = |coordinates = |start_date = |completion_date = 26 July 1986 |demolition_date = 1993 |height = |diameter = |other_dimensions = |floor_count = 3 |floor_area = |main_contractor = |architect = |structural_engineer = |services_engineer = |civil_engineer = |other_designers = |quantity_surveyor = |awards = }} The '''tea house''' was a public building in the city of [[Agdam]], [[Azerbaijan]].
==History== The tea house was based on the idea of the academician Khudu Mammadov during Sadig Murtuzayev’s post as first Secretary of the Agdam District Party Committee of the Central Committee of the Azerbaijan SSR. Naik Samadov was chief architect of the Tea House project. In the project, masonry was only used on the first floor. The remainder consisted of metal construction. It was decided to place the tea house near the mosque after discussion with Khudu Mammadov. [[Penal labor]] was used to reduce construction costs.<ref name="cayevi">{{cite web|title= Ağdamın simvolu - Çay evi |url= http://modern.az/articles/63623/1/#gsc.tab=0|publisher= modern.az|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref> The tea house was inaugurated on 26 July 1986. In addition to the regional officials, [[Vafa Guluzade]], the head of the Culture Department of the CP CC of Azerbaijan SSR, also participated in the opening ceremony.<ref name="cayevi"/> The article published in the July 31, 1986, issue of “The Lenin Path”, on the occasion of the opening of the tea house, reads: {{cquote|''"After the decision of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union on the "Drunkenness and Alcoholization Measures", our district has a lot of activities. The Tea House, which is being used today, is of great importance in this respect. Role of the Tea House is indispensable for the workers to spend their leisure time effectively."'' <ref>" The Lenin Path" newspaper (Aghdam). 31 July 1986</ref> }} In 1993, the Tea House was burned down by the [[Armenian Armed Forces]].<ref name="cayevied">{{cite web|title= Quzanlıda Ağdam şəhərindəki məşhur çay evinin bənzəri tikilib|url= https://azertag.az/xeber/Quzanlida_Agdam_seherindeki_meshur_chay_evinin_benzeri_tikilib-855145|publisher= azertag.az|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref>
===Design=== A large diameter pipe was placed in the middle of the tea house. On each side, small volumes of tubes were merged with structures. Floors were wooden. Pipes were embellished with wood and decorated with various ornaments. Each floor had four doors. The dome of the tea house was roofed with galvanized iron.<ref name="cayevi"/>
===Tea house in Kuzanly === On May 10, 2015, a copy of the tea house was built in [[Kuzanly|Guzanli]] settlement of Aghdam region.<ref name="cayevied"/>
